On 11 August, 2022 Nic and I talked about how this could be another way to pull out mineralogy information. Could grab "smectitic" or "mixed" from these names if we wanted to do yes/no variable. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} target_comp %>% pull(taxclname) %>% unique() %>% head() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] "Sandy over clayey, mixed over smectitic, frigid Typic Calciaquolls" [2] "Sandy over clayey, mixed over smectitic, frigid Aquic Calciudolls" [3] "Mixed, frigid Aquic Udipsamments" [4] "Fine, smectitic, frigid Typic Epiaquerts" [5] "Sandy, mixed, frigid Typic Endoaquolls" [6] "Sandy, mixed, frigid Aeric Calciaquolls" ``` ::: ::: ## Variables of Interest I think my next step is to use the `chorizon` table and pull the variables I'm interested in for each of my major components. Devine et al. 2021 did 0-30cm depth-weighted averages. I am going to do 0-20cm because I believe this is more likely to be the available depth in our validation datasets (esp. CIG). Then I can [turn my horizon table into an SPC object](http://ncss-tech.github.io/AQP/demos/profileApply/loafercreek.html#26_build-your-own_spcs), with cokey as "site"? ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} chorizon <- mn_components <- sf::st_read(dsn = mn_gdb, layer = "chorizon") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Reading layer `chorizon' from data source `C:\Users\Hava\Documents\R\ch03-sh-cluster\data\gSSURGO_MN\gSSURGO_MN.gdb' using driver `OpenFileGDB' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: no simple feature geometries present: returning a data.frame or tbl_df ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} target_horiz <- chorizon %>% filter(cokey %in% maj_comp$cokey) ``` ::: ## Diagnostic Features {#sec-diag-feat} Here, I'm pulling out the depth to restrictive horizon (if any) in the profile.
